    <h1>Theory-testing in psychology and physics</h1>
    <p class="text-gray-400 text-sm mb-6">Paul E. Meehl · 1967 · <a href="https://www.cambridge.org/core/journals/philosophy-of-science/article/theorytesting-in-psychology-and-physics-a-methodological-paradox/F6CDBDBE5D960C356178BDA5D87EB4BC">Philosophy of Science 34(2), 103–115</a></p>

    <div class="bg-zinc-800 rounded-lg p-5 mb-8 callout">
      <p class="text-lg" style="max-width:none">In physics, sharper instruments make theories harder to corroborate. In psychology, more data makes the null easier to reject. Identical method, opposite direction. The field that moves faster is the one where success is harder to fake.</p>
